{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"84334f07-76d6-40df-9883-357bfa32ee68","content":"## What's happening\n\n.NET 11 raised the **x86-64 baseline architecture level**. Previous .NET versions required only x86-64-v1 (SSE/SSE2), but .NET 11 likely requires **x86-64-v2** (adds SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT) or **x86-64-v3** (adds AVX2, FMA, BMI1/BMI2).\n\nYour 2012-era hardware (likely Sandy Bridge / Ivy Bridge Xeons) supports AVX but **not AVX2** (introduced with Haswell in 2013). If the new baseline is v3, those nodes will fail at startup with that exact error.\n\n## Your other platforms are fine because:\n- **Windows Arm64 (SQ1):** Arm has its own baseline; not affected by x86 changes\n- **Raspberry Pi 4 (Arm64 Linux):** Same — separate Arm64 baseline\n\n## Options\n\n1. **Replace the old hardware** with Haswell-era (2013+) or newer CPUs\n2. **Pin those nodes to .NET 10** until hardware refresh\n3. Check if the .NET 11 SDK offers a compatibility switch or a build that targets a lower baseline (check release notes for `DOTNET_EnableSSE41` / `DOTNET_baseline` style knobs — though runtime baseline requirements typically can't be lowered)\n\nRun `lscpu` on the failing node and look at the `Flags` line to confirm which instructions are missing.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d35bdad1-71ef-4a61-a76a-c4199913e568","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me explain what's happening.\n\nThis is about .NET's hardware baseline requirements. Starting with .NET 9, there were discussions about raising the x86-64 baseline, and .NET 11 (hypothetical future version) likely raised the x86-64 baseline architecture level.\n\nLet me think about what I know:\n\n- x86-64 has microarchitecture levels:\n  - x86-64-v1: Original AMD64/Intel 64 baseline (SSE, SSE2)\n  - x86-64-v2: Added SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT, CMPXCHG16B\n  - x86-64-v3: Added AVX, AVX2, BMI1, BMI2, F16C, FMA, LZCNT, MOVBE\n  - x86-64-v4: Added AVX-512\n\n.NET 8 raised the baseline for x86-64 to effectively require SSE/SSE2 (which was already the case). There have been discussions about raising to x86-64-v2 or potentially higher in future versions.\n\nThe error \"The current CPU is missing one or more of the baseline instruction sets\" is a real .NET runtime error that occurs when the CPU doesn't meet the minimum instruction set requirements. If .NET 11 were to raise the baseline to x86-64-v2, older hardware from around 2012 might struggle, though most Intel CPUs from that era like Sandy Bridge and Ivy Bridge actually do support SSE4.2 and POPCNT.\n\nHowever, if the baseline jumped to x86-64-v3 (requiring AVX2), that would explain the failure—Sandy Bridge and Ivy Bridge only have AVX, not AVX2, which wasn't introduced until Haswell in 2013. Given the user's scenario of 2012 hardware failing on .NET 11, this seems like the most plausible explanation. I'm recalling that .NET 9 had proposals to raise the baseline, and since the user's scenario is hypothetical with .NET 11, the most likely explanation is they bumped the x86-64 baseline to either v2 or v3, which would exclude older hardware like Sandy Bridge if it was v3 (requiring AVX2). So the most likely explanation is that .NET 11 bumped the baseline instruction set to x86-64-v3, which requires AVX2 and other features that didn't arrive until Haswell in 2013—meaning 2012-era hardware like Sandy Bridge or Ivy Bridge Xeons would fall short of that requirement.","outputTokens":1976,"requestId":"C431:28D4C6:1D038E7:20D559D:6A07C8CE"},"id":"6148a537-e9db-4e66-8a7c-d9250196a1c4","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:31:31.445Z","parentId":"627a29d3-8ac0-4a1d-a847-957a50a14f65"}
